<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99425022747230></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99425022747230><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=7&mid=99425022747230>General</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Jul 4th 8:37 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Having read this entire forum, I would like to try to answer several of the questions which are raised.<br><br>In terms of which race to play... basically, it doesn't matter.  The stats which you will need to maximize at the end of the game are WIS, mana, and resists.. but WIS is fairly easy to get to its soft cap (which is 200) for a high level cleric.<br><br>I suggest that if you are aiming for the end game, you choose a race with a graphic which you like, or one which has special abilities which are helpful.  Personally I play a Dark Elf cleric because of the nightvision, the fact that they can hide whilst medding, and the fact that I like the graphic :o)<br><br>If you only plan to play your cleric occasionally and you want an easy time of it, Dwarves and High Elves are about equally good as choices.<br><br>In terms of what stat you need to max out... the person who posted about getting high AC is correct, at lower levels.  High AC and (to a lesser extent) high HP will help prevent you from getting killed.<br><br>By the time you get to the mid levels (25-45), you should be working on getting your wisdom to 200.  This is not overly challenging given the number of wisdom-boosting items in the game.  Once your wisdom is at 200 (which is a soft cap... there is very little benefit in getting wisdom higher, although theoretically it can get to 255), you should be working on mana-boosting items also.  You will also find that your AC is dropping behind those of the tanks in the party.  Do not be overly concerned about this if you are aiming for the end game.  By the time you are fighting King Tormax (or whatever), you will know that he will hit you for maximum damage whether your AC is 1 or 1200.  (Incidentally, yes, it is possible to get AC over 1000).  If you want to be a cleric, high AC is no substitute for learning to control your aggro.<br><br>Your extra equipment slots should be devoted to achieving a balance between the various resists.  It is impossible to overstate the value of resists in the end game.  Also, some items which boost your HP will be helpful.<br><br>About the issue of two people playing on the same account at the same time... no, you can't.  People who are thinking about it should read the declaration at the beginning of the game (you know, where you click 'I accept' before you can get in ?)<br><br>To the people who are wondering where to hunt... the answer is Kunark if you're after fast experience (but the loot sucks).  However, you should be aware that eventually you will be going into dungeons and camping for cool items.  You should practice doing this wherever you can.  Dungeon experience is crucial.<br><br>It is also important to make friends during these levels.  Find several enchanters and several tanks who you like, you trust, and who trust you.  Group with these people as much as possible.<br><br>Also, you are well advised to look for a decent guild to join.  At the high end of the game, most raids are guild raids... a character without a good guild is unlikely ever to get his or her planes armour, Water Sprinkler of Nem Ankh, or whatever.<br><br>To the people who say, "Clerics can't solo", the answer is yes, they can.  I soloed my cleric at various times between levels 44 and 47 against the tree spectre in Feerrott using enstill and banish undead (root & nuke tactics).<br><br>To the people who say, "I like to solo"... you have chosen the wrong class.  Give up and make a druid or necro.  Clerics are about grouping.<br><br>I must admit that I have *no* idea why someone would purchase an online game and then play by themselves, and I have *no* idea how a toon who insists on soloing all the time is ever going to get their epic or their planes armour.  Nobody can get their epic quest without lots of help, and that means friends.  Friends come from grouping with people and helping people, not kiting mobs by yourself.  Having said that, I know a lot of people who solo and who say that they enjoy it, so good luck to them I suppose.<br><br>Kind of a long post, but I hope it helps :o)<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
