<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99477179413815></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99477179413815><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=7&mid=99477179413815>RE: General</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jul 10th 9:29 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Thank you :o)<br><br>Since I made my original post I notice that the discussion about AC vs. aggro control is continuing.  To those who still think clerics need high AC at high level, can I make the following points ?<br><br>Get a higher AC in preference to high wisdom at low level, sure.  Your tanks at this level may well be inexperienced and less effective at taunting than they might be... besides which, high WIS means relatively little at these levels.<br><br>As soon as you get the Atone spell (I think it was level 34, but I could be wrong, it was a while ago /grin ) then you should ensure that you have it memmed if you are not confident with your aggro control.<br><br>The Atone spell is similar to the enchanter's mem-blur spell in that it wipes the monster's hate list.  After casting a heal, Atone the monster to reduce the risk of it attacking you.  However, you MUST inform your group that you are Atoning the monster so that the tanks know to taunt it at once.  Also, if there is an enchanter in the group, do not use this spell... it is the proper role of the enchanter to manage the mob's hate list and he or she will not appreciate your interference.<br><br>The Celestial Healing spell (at level 44) is very important to acquire.  Not only is it mana-efficient, but it appears to have a very low taunt value for the amount of healing it does.  Use Cele Heal whenever possible.<br><br>You WILL learn how to deal with a Feign Death puller (a monk or a level 30+ shadowknight).  Healing someone who is FD will teach you a lot about aggro control... and it is a mistake that you will not repeat.<br><br>SUMMARY<br><br>1) Group with an enchanter whenever possible.  Let the enchanter manage the mob's hate list.<br><br>2) Use low-taunt spells such as Cele Heal.<br><br>3) Have root, DA and DB memmed at ALL times whether or not you think you need them.  Have atone memmed when alone, with groups without an enchanter, or in situations where you are not certain about your group's ability to control aggro.<br><br>4) Stand up when mobs are near.  Sitting down has a high taunt value.  If you are a DE or Halfling, hide whilst medding.<br><br>5) Be aware of where everyone in the group is.  Do not heal a FD puller without permission unless you can SEE them.  If you cannot see them, wait for them to ask to be healed.  If they do not ask, you are permitted to ask them, "%t may I heal you ?" - but NEVER heal someone who is FD.<br><br>Learn these things and by the time you get to the end game, you will not need AC.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
